C News]]\n*Sara Murray \u2013 [[CNN]]\n*[[Sophia A. Nelson]] \u2013 ''[[Jet Magazine]]''\n*[[Norah O'Donnell]] \u2013 [[NBC News]], [[MSNBC]], [[CBS News]]\n*[[Susan Page]] \u2013 ''[[USA Today]]''\n*[[John Palmer (TV journalist)|John Palmer]] \u2013 [[NBC News]]\n*[[Scott Pelley]] \u2013 [[CBS News]]\n*[[Bill Plante]] \u2013 [[CBS News]]\n*[[Sean Quinn (writer)|Sean Quinn]] \u2013 ''[[FiveThirtyEight.com]]''\n*[[Martha Raddatz]] \u2013 [[ABC News]]\n*[[Margaret Brennan]] \u2013 [[CBS News]]<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/02/11/us/politics/sean-spicer-white-house-press-briefing.html |title=All Joking Aside, Here's How Sean Spicer is Shaking Up the White House Press Briefing |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=February 11, 2017 |accessdate=February 11, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Dan Rather]] \u2013 [[CBS News]]\n*[[Chip Reid]] \u2013 [[CBS News]]\n*[[John D. Roberts]] \u2013 [[CBS News]]\n*Arlette Saenz \u2013 [[ABC News]], [[CNN]]\n*[[Bill Sammon]] \u2013 ''[[The Washington Times]]'', ''[[The Washington Examiner]]''\n*[[Bob Schieffer]] \u2013 [[CBS News]]\n*[[Ari Shapiro]] \u2013 [[National Public Radio]] \n*[[Claire Shipman]] \u2013 [[NBC News]]\n*[[Hugh Sidey]] \u2013 ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''\n*[[Mark Smith (journalist)|Mark Smith]] \u2013 ''[[Associated Press]]''\n*[[Paul Sperry]] \u2013 ''[[Investor's Business Daily]]''\n*[[Lesley Stahl]] \u2013 [[CBS News]]\n*[[Jake Tapper]] \u2013 [[ABC News]]\n*[[Helen Thomas]] \u2013 [[Hearst (media)|Hearst Newspapers]], [[United Press International]]\n*[[Robert E Thompson|Bob Thompson]] \u2013 [[Hearst (media)|Hearst Newspapers]]\n*[[Chuck Todd]] \u2013 [[NBC News]]\n*[[Alvin Toffler]] \u2013 ''York Gazette Daily''\n*[[Jim VandeHei]] \u2013 ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n*[[Mike Viqueira]] \u2013 [[Al Jazeera America]]\n*[[Chris Wallace (journalist)|Chris Wallace]] \u2013 [[NBC News]]\n*[[Brian Williams]] \u2013 [[NBC News]]\n*[[Juan Williams]] \u2013 ''[[The Washington Post]]''\n*[[Richard Wolffe]] \u2013 ''[[Newsweek]]''\n*[[Judy Woodruff]] \u2013 [[NBC News]]\n*[[Byron York]] \u2013 ''[[National Review]]''\n{{div col end}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Journalism}}\n*[[Press gallery]]\n*[[Canberra Press Gallery]]\n*[[Kremlin Pool]]\n*[[Press Secretary]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.whca.net/index.htm White House Correspondents' Association official website]\n\n{{White House press corps}}\n{{White House James S. Brady Press Briefing Room Seating Chart}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:White House press corps}}\n[[Category:American political media]]\n[[Category:White House]]\n[[Category:American journalism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Group of journalists or correspondents usually stationed at the White House in Washington, D.C.}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2017}}\n[[File:Acting Commissioner of CBP Mark Morgan Speaks to Reporters (48708163577).jpg|thumb|Reporters ask questions at a White House Press Briefing in 2019]]\nThe '''White House press corps''' is the group of [[journalists]], [[correspondents]], or members of the media usually stationed at the [[White House]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], to cover the [[president of the United States]], White House events, and news briefings. Their offices are located in the [[West Wing]].\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:The Prime Minister of the Czech Republic and Mrs. Monika Babi\u0161ov\u00e1 Visit the White House (40353221263).jpg|thumb|Photographers and videographers in the [[Oval Office]] in 2019]]\n[[File:White House Press Corp outside.jpg|thumb|Semi-permanent setup of press corps on the west end of the north White House lawn, from where live media broadcasts with the White House are typically delivered]]\nThe [[White House Press Secretary|White House press secretary]] or a deputy generally holds a weekday news briefing in the [[James S. Brady Press Briefing Room]]. The room currently seats 49 reporters. Each seat is assigned to a news gathering organization, with the most prominent organizations occupying the first two rows. Reporters who do not have an assigned seat may stand. Often a smaller group of reporters known as the \"White House press pool\" is assembled to report back to their colleagues on events where the venue would make open coverage logistically difficult.{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\nWhen a new U.S. president is elected, some news organizations change their correspondents, most often to the reporter who had been assigned to cover the new president during the preceding campaign. For example, after the [[2008 United States presidential election|2008 presidential campaign]], ABC News moved [[Jake Tapper]], who had covered [[Barack Obama]] during his presidential campaign, to the White House correspondent's position.{{Citation needed|date=July 2016}}\n\n==History==\nThe White House press corps had their first duties in the White House in the early 1900s. An [[urban legend]] exists of [[President Theodore Roosevelt]] noticing a group of correspondents in the rain looking for sources for their stories and inviting them into the White House. Subsequent historical research outlines how reporters were able to start with small stories in the White House and then grew their presence and influence over a span of many years.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.whca.net/history.htm | title = HISTORY OF THE WHCA | work = WHCA | publisher = White House Correspondents' Association  | date = }}</ref>\n\n==Correspondents==\n\n===Current===\n\nOrdered by [[James S. Brady Press Briefing Room]] seating chart. Reporters listed by last name, unless designated as \"chief\" or \"senior\" by news organization\n\n====Television====\n \n*[[NBC News]]/[[MSNBC]] \u2013 [[Hallie Jackson]], [[Peter Alexander (journalist)|Peter Alexander]], Geoff Bennett<ref>https://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/geoff-bennett-joins-nbc-news-as-white-house-correspondent/344528/</ref>, [[Kelly O'Donnell]], [[Shannon Pettypiece]], [[Kristen Welker]] \n*[[Fox News]]/[[Fox Business]] \u2013 [[John Roberts (journalist)|John Roberts]], Blake Burman, [[Kevin Corke]]\n*[[CBS News]]/[[CBSN]]<ref>https://www.cbsnews.com/team/</ref> \u2013 [[Major Garrett]], Sara Cook<ref>https://twitter.com/saraecook</ref>, Paula Reid, [[Ben Tracy]]\n*[[ABC News]] \u2013 [[Jonathan Karl]], [[Devin Dwyer]], Katherine Faulders<ref>https://twitter.com/KFaulders</ref>, Jon Garcia<ref>https://twitter.com/GarciaJon</ref>, John R. Parkinson<ref>https://twitter.com/jparkABC</ref>, Jordyn Phelps<ref>https://twitter.com/JordynPhelps</ref>, [[Cecilia Vega (anchor)|Cecilia Vega]]\n*[[CNN]]<ref>https://www.cnn.com/specials/profiles</ref> \u2013 [[Jim Acosta]], Kate Bennett, [[Kaitlan Collins]], Stephen Collinson, [[Jeremy Diamond]], Kevin Liptak, Allie Malloy, [[Jeff Zeleny]] \n*[[CNBC]] \u2013 Eamon Javers<ref>https://twitter.com/EamonJavers</ref>, [[Kayla Tausche]], Christina Wilkie<ref>https://twitter.com/christinawilkie</ref>\n*[[Telemundo]] \u2013 Maria Pe\u00f1a<ref>https://twitter.com/mariauxpen</ref>\n*Foreign Press \u2013 Takaaki Abe ([[Nippon TV]]), Gustau Alegret ([[NTN24]])<ref>https://twitter.com/GustauAlegret</ref>, Nadia Bilbassy ([[Al Arabiya]])<ref>https://twitter.com/nadia_bilbassy</ref>, Ching-Yi Chang ([[Shanghai Media Group]]), Philip Crowther ([[France 24]])<ref>https://twitter.com/PhilipinDC</ref>, Peter Kleim ([[n-tv]]), Raquel Kr\u00e4henb\u00fchl ([[GloboNews]])<ref>https://twitter.com/Rkrahenbuhl</ref>, [[Richard Latendresse]] ([[TVA Group]]), Cordelia Lynch ([[Sky News]])<ref>https://twitter.com/CordeliaSkyNews</ref>, [[Joy Malbon]] ([[CTV News]])\n*Regional Press \u2013 [[Scott Thuman]] ([[Sinclair Broadcast Group]])\n*[[PBS]] \u2013 [[Yamiche Alcindor]]\n*[[Al Jazeera English]] \u2013 [[Alan Fisher (broadcast journalist)|Alan Fisher]], [[Kimberly Halkett]]\n*[[Newsmax TV]] \u2013 Emerald Robinson<ref>https://www.newsmax.com/newsfront/newsmax-tv-emerald-robinson-media-white-house-correspondent/2020/02/11/id/953545/</ref>, John Gizzi<ref>https://twi