{"title_page": "Melengestrol acetate", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Megestrol acetate}}\n{{Drugbox\n| IUPAC_name = [(8''R'',9''S'',10''R'',13''S'',14''S'',17''R'')-17-acetyl-6,10,13-trimethyl-16-methylidene-3-oxo-1,2,8,9,11,12,14,15-octahydrocyclopenta[a]phenanthren-17-yl] acetate\n| image = Melengestrol acetate.svg\n| width = 225px\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename = Heifermax, MGA\n| pregnancy_category = \n| legal_status = \n| routes_of_administration = \n| class = [[Progestogen (medication)|Progestogen]]; [[Progestin]]; [[Progestogen ester]]\n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability = \n| protein_bound = \n| metabolism = \n| elimination_half-life = \n| excretion = \n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number = 2919-66-6\n| CAS_supplemental = \n| UNII_Ref = {{fdacite|correct|FDA}}\n| UNII = 4W5HDS3936\n| ATC_prefix = None\n| ATC_suffix = \n| PubChem = 250948\n| ChemSpiderID = 219803\n| KEGG = D04900\n| synonyms = MGA; MLA; MLGA; Melengesterol acetate; Methylsuperlutin; U-21240; BDH-1921; 17\u03b1-Acetoxy-16-methylene-6-methyl-6-dehydroprogesterone; 17\u03b1-Acetoxy-16-methylene-6-methylpregna-4,6-diene-3,20-dione\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=25 | H=32 | O=4\n| molecular_weight = 396.519 g/mol\n| SMILES = O=C4\\C=C3\\C(=C/[C@@H]1[C@H](CC[C@@]2([C@](OC(=O)C)(C(=C)\\C[C@@H]12)C(=O)C)C)[C@@]3(C)CC4)C\n| StdInChI = 1S/C25H32O4/c1-14-11-19-20(23(5)9-7-18(28)13-21(14)23)8-10-24(6)22(19)12-15(2)25(24,16(3)26)29-17(4)27/h11,13,19-20,22H,2,7-10,12H2,1,3-6H3/t19-,20+,22+,23-,24+,25+/m1/s1\n| StdInChIKey = UDKABVSQKJNZBH-DWNQPYOZSA-N\n}}\n\n'''Melengestrol acetate''' ('''MLGA'''), sold under the brand names '''Heifermax''' and '''MGA''' among others, is a [[progestin]] medication which is used in [[animal reproduction]].<ref name=\"Elks2014\">{{cite book|author=J. Elks|title=The Dictionary of Drugs: Chemical Data: Chemical Data, Structures and Bibliographies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0vXTBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA764|date=14 November 2014|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-4757-2085-3|pages=764\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Drugs.com\">https://www.drugs.com/international/melengestrol.html</ref> It is not approved for use in humans, and is instead used as an implantable [[contraceptive]] for captive animals in zoos and other refuges,<ref name=\"AsaContra10\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a1vev5hf7o8C&pg=PA469 |chapter=Chapter 34: Contraception as a Management Tool for Controlling Surplus Animals |title=Wild Mammals in Captivity: Principles and Techniques for Zoo Management |edition=2nd |author1=Asa, C.S. |author2=Porton, I.J. |editor1=Kleiman, D.G. |editor2=Thompson, K.V. |editor3=Baer, C.K. |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago, IL |year=2010 |pages=469\u2013482 |isbn=9780226440118 |accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> and is also used as a [[feed additive]] to [[natural growth promoter|promote growth]] in [[cattle]], a purpose it is licensed for in the [[United States]] and [[Canada]].<ref name=\"Kay2009\">{{cite book | author = Jack F. Kay | title = Analyses for Hormonal Substances in Food-Producing Animals | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9V-DbnzZiiMC&pg=PA139 | accessdate = 27 May 2012 | date = 26 November 2009 | publisher = Royal Society of Chemistry | isbn = 978-0-85404-198-5 | page = 139}}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\n\n===Animal reproduction===\nMLGA is used in [[animal reproduction]].<ref name=\"AsaContra10\" /><ref name=\"Kay2009\" />\n\n==Pharmacology==\n\n===Pharmacodynamics===\nMLGA is a [[progestogen (medication)|progestogen]], and hence is an [[agonist]] of the [[progesterone receptor]].<ref name=\"pmid405534\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Illingworth DV, Elsner C, De Groot K, Flickinger GL, Mikhail G | title = A specific progesterone receptor of myometrial cytosol from the rhesus monkey | journal = J. Steroid Biochem. | volume = 8 | issue = 2 | pages = 157\u201360 | date = February 1977 | pmid = 405534 | doi = 10.1016/0022-4731(77)90040-1| url = }}</ref> It has been found to possess 73% of the [[affinity (pharmacology)|affinity]] of [[progesterone (medication)|progesterone]] for the progesterone receptor in [[rhesus monkey]] [[uterus]].<ref name=\"pmid405534\" />\n\n==Chemistry==\n{{See also|List of progestogens|Progestogen ester|List of progestogen esters}}\n\nMLGA, also known as 17\u03b1-acetoxy-16-methylene-6-dehydro-6-methylprogesterone or as 17\u03b1-acetoxy-16-methylene-6-methylpregna-4,6-diene-3,20-dione, is a [[synthetic compound|synthetic]] [[pregnane]] [[steroid]] and a [[chemical derivative|derivative]] of [[progesterone]].<ref name=\"Elks2014\" /><ref name=\"Drugs.com\" /> It is specifically a derivative of [[17\u03b1-hydroxyprogesterone]] with a [[methyl group]] at the C6 position, a [[methylene group]] at the C16 position, a [[double bond]] between the C6 and C7 positions, and an [[acetate]] [[ester]] at the C17\u03b1 position.<ref name=\"Elks2014\" /><ref name=\"Drugs.com\" /> As such, it is also a derivative of [[16-methylene-17\u03b1-hydroxyprogesterone acetate]]. MLGA is the [[acetate]] [[ester]] of [[melengestrol]], which in contrast, has never been marketed.<ref name=\"Elks2014\" /> [[Structural analogue|Analogue]]s of MLGA include other 17\u03b1-hydroxyprogesterone derivatives such as [[chlormadinone acetate]], [[chlormethenmadinone acetate]], [[cyproterone acetate]], [[delmadinone acetate]], [[hydroxyprogesterone caproate]], [[medroxyprogesterone acetate]], [[megestrol acetate]], [[methenmadinone acetate]], and [[osaterone acetate]].<ref name=\"Elks2014\" /> The only structural difference between MLGA and [[megestrol acetate]] is the presence of the C16 methylene group in the former.<ref name=\"Elks2014\" />\n\n==Society and culture==\n\n===Generic names===\n''Melengestrol acetate'' is the [[generic term|generic name]] of the drug and its {{abbrlink|USAN|United States Adopted Name}} and {{abbrlink|USP|United States Pharmacopeia}}.<ref name=\"Elks2014\" /><ref name=\"Drugs.com\" /> ''Melengestrol'' is the {{abbrlink|INN|International Nonproprietary Name}} and {{abbrlink|BAN|British Approved Name}} of the unesterified free [[alcohol]] form.<ref name=\"Elks2014\" /><ref name=\"Drugs.com\" />\n\n===Brand names===\nMLGA is marketed under the brand names Heifermax and MGA among others.<ref name=\"Elks2014\" /><ref name=\"Drugs.com\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{Progestogens and antiprogestogens}}\n{{Progesterone receptor modulators}}\n\n[[Category:Acetate esters]]\n[[Category:Antineoplastic drugs]]\n[[Category:Pregnanes]]\n[[Category:Progestogen esters]]\n[[Category:Progestogens]]\n[[Category:Veterinary drugs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Megestrol acetate}}\n{{Drugbox\n| IUPAC_name = [(8''R'',9''S'',10''R'',13''S'',14''S'',17''R'')-17-acetyl-6,10,13-trimethyl-16-methylidene-3-oxo-1,2,8,9,11,12,14,15-octahydrocyclopenta[a]phenanthren-17-yl] acetate\n| image = Melengestrol acetate.svg\n| width = 225px\n\n<!--Clinical data-->\n| tradename = Heifermax, MGA\n| pregnancy_category = \n| legal_status = \n| routes_of_administration = \n| class = [[Progestogen (medication)|Progestogen]]; [[Progestin]]; [[Progestogen ester]]\n\n<!--Pharmacokinetic data-->\n| bioavailability = \n| protein_bound = \n| metabolism = \n| elimination_half-life = \n| excretion = \n\n<!--Identifiers-->\n| CAS_number = 2919-66-6\n| CAS_supplemental = \n| ATC_prefix = None\n| ATC_suffix = \n| PubChem = 250948\n| ChemSpiderID = 219803\n| KEGG = D04900\n| synonyms = MGA; MLA; MLGA; Melengesterol acetate; Methylsuperlutin; U-21240; BDH-1921; 17\u03b1-Acetoxy-16-methylene-6-methyl-6-dehydroprogesterone; 17\u03b1-Acetoxy-16-methylene-6-methylpregna-4,6-diene-3,20-dione\n\n<!--Chemical data-->\n| C=25 | H=32 | O=4\n| molecular_weight = 396.519 g/mol\n| SMILES = O=C4\\C=C3\\C(=C/[C@@H]1[C@H](CC[C@@]2([C@](OC(=O)C)(C(=C)\\C[C@@H]12)C(=O)C)C)[C@@]3(C)CC4)C\n| StdInChI = 1S/C25H32O4/c1-14-11-19-20(23(5)9-7-18(28)13-21(14)23)8-10-24(6)22(19)12-15(2)25(24,16(3)26)29-17(4)27/h11,13,19-20,22H,2,7-10,12H2,1,3-6H3/t19-,20+,22+,23-,24+,25+/m1/s1\n| StdInChIKey = UDKABVSQKJNZBH-DWNQPYOZSA-N\n}}\n\n'''Melengestrol acetate''' ('''MLGA'''), sold under the brand names '''Heifermax''' and '''MGA''' among others, is a [[progestin]] medication which is used in [[animal reproduction]].<ref name=\"Elks2014\">{{cite book|author=J. Elks|title=The Dictionary of Drugs: Chemical Data: Chemical Data, Structures and Bibliographies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0vXTBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA764|date=14 November 2014|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-1-4757-2085-3|pages=764\u2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Drugs.com\">https://www.drugs.com/international/melengestrol.html</ref> It is not approved for use in humans, and is instead used as an implantable [[contraceptive]] for captive animals in zoos and other refuges,<ref name=\"AsaContra10\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a1vev5hf7o8C&pg=PA469 |chapter=Chapter 34: Contraception as a Management Tool for Controlling Surplus Animals |title=Wild Mammals in Captivity: Principles and Techniques for Zoo Management |edition=2nd |author1=Asa, C.S. |author2=Porton, I.J. |editor1=Kleiman, D.G. |editor2=Thompson, K.V. |editor3=Baer, C.K. |publisher=University of Chicago Press |location=Chicago, IL |year=2010 |pages=469\u2013482 |isbn=9780226440118 |accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref> and is also used as a [[feed additive]] to [[natural growth promoter|promote growth]] in [[cattle]], a purpose it is licensed for in the [[United States]] and [[Canada]].<ref name=\"Kay2009\">{{cite book | author = Jack F. Kay | title = Analyses for Hormonal Substances in Food-Producing Animals | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9V-DbnzZiiMC&pg=PA139 | accessdate = 27 May 2012 | date = 26 November 2009 | publisher = Royal Society of Chemistry | isbn = 978-0-85404-198-5 | page = 139}}</ref>\n\n==Uses==\n\n===Animal reproduction===\nMLGA is used in [[animal reproduction]].<ref name=\"AsaContra10\" /><ref name=\"Kay2009\" />\n\n==Pharmacology==\n\n===Pharmacodynamics===\nMLGA is a [[progestogen (medication)|progestogen]], and hence is an [[agonist]] of the [[progesterone receptor]].<ref name=\"pmid405534\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Illingworth DV, Elsner C, De Groot K, Flickinger GL, Mikhail G | title = A specific progesterone receptor of myometrial cytosol from the rhesus monkey | journal = J. Steroid Biochem. | volume = 8 | issue = 2 | pages = 157\u201360 | date = February 1977 | pmid = 405534 | doi = 10.1016/0022-4731(77)90040-1| url = }}</ref> It has been found to possess 73% of the [[affinity (pharmacology)|affinity]] of [[progesterone (medication)|progesterone]] for the progesterone receptor in [[rhesus monkey]] [[uterus]].<ref name=\"pmid405534\" />\n\n==Chemistry==\n{{See also|List of progestogens|Progestogen ester|List of progestogen esters}}\n\nMLGA, also known as 17\u03b1-acetoxy-16-methylene-6-dehydro-6-methylprogesterone or as 17\u03b1-acetoxy-16-methylene-6-methylpregna-4,6-diene-3,20-dione, is a [[synthetic compound|synthetic]] [[pregnane]] [[steroid]] and a [[chemical derivative|derivative]] of [[progesterone]].<ref name=\"Elks2014\" /><ref name=\"Drugs.com\" /> It is specifically a derivative of [[17\u03b1-hydroxyprogesterone]] with a [[methyl group]] at the C6 position, a [[methylene group]] at the C16 position, a [[double bond]] between the C6 and C7 positions, and an [[acetate]] [[ester]] at the C17\u03b1 position.<ref name=\"Elks2014\" /><ref name=\"Drugs.com\" /> As such, it is also a derivative of [[16-methylene-17\u03b1-hydroxyprogesterone acetate]]. MLGA is the [[acetate]] [[ester]] of [[melengestrol]], which in contrast, has never been marketed.<ref name=\"Elks2014\" /> [[Structural analogue|Analogue]]s of MLGA include other 17\u03b1-hydroxyprogesterone derivatives such as [[chlormadinone acetate]], [[chlormethenmadinone acetate]], [[cyproterone acetate]], [[delmadinone acetate]], [[hydroxyprogesterone caproate]], [[medroxyprogesterone acetate]], [[megestrol acetate]], [[methenmadinone acetate]], and [[osaterone acetate]].<ref name=\"Elks2014\" /> The only structural difference between MLGA and [[megestrol acetate]] is the presence of the C16 methylene group in the former.<ref name=\"Elks2014\" />\n\n==Society and culture==\n\n===Generic names===\n''Melengestrol acetate'' is the [[generic term|generic name]] of the drug and its {{abbrlink|USAN|United States Adopted Name}} and {{abbrlink|USP|United States Pharmacopeia}}.<ref name=\"Elks2014\" /><ref name=\"Drugs.com\" /> ''Melengestrol'' is the {{abbrlink|INN|International Nonproprietary Name}} and {{abbrlink|BAN|British Approved Name}} of the unesterified free [[alcohol]] form.<ref name=\"Elks2014\" /><ref name=\"Drugs.com\" />\n\n===Brand names===\nMLGA is marketed under the brand names Heifermax and MGA among others.<ref name=\"Elks2014\" /><ref name=\"Drugs.com\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n{{Progestogens and antiprogestogens}}\n{{Progesterone receptor modulators}}\n\n[[Category:Acetate esters]]\n[[Category:Antineoplastic drugs]]\n[[Category:Pregnanes]]\n[[Category:Progestogen esters]]\n[[Category:Progestogens]]\n[[Category:Veterinary drugs]]\n", "name_user": "Fswitzer4", "label": "safe", "comment": "added FDA UNII to drug box", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melengestrol_acetate"}
{"title_page": "Eddie Large", "text_new": "{{short description|British comedian}}\n{{Recent death}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date= March  2020}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name              = Eddie Large\n| image             = Eddie Large.jpg\n| imagesize         = 180px\n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = Edward Hugh McGinnis\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1941|6|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|2020|4|2|1941|6|25|df=y}}\n| death_place       = [[Southmead Hospital]], [[Bristol]], England \n| medium            = Comedian\n| nationality       = Scottish\n| genre             = \n| subject           = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| spouse            = {{ubl|{{marriage|Sandra Bigwood|1965||end=div}}|{{marriage|Patsy Ann Scott|1983|<!--Year is omitted when marriage ends by death of subject of article-->}}}} \n| children          = 3\n| notable_work      = [[Little and Large]]\n}}\n\n'''Edward Hugh McGinnis''' (25 June 1941 \u2013 2 April 2020), better known by the stage name '''Eddie Large''', was a Scottish comedian. He was best known as one half of the double act [[Little and Large]], with [[Syd Little]].\n\n==Early life==  \nLarge was born Edward Hugh McGinnis in [[Glasgow]] in 1941. His father Teddy served as a [[Petty Officer]] in the [[Royal Navy]] during World War II and after he returned from the war the family moved to a [[tenement]] in [[Oatlands, Glasgow|Oatlands]].<ref name=Autobiography>{{cite book|date=1 July 2005|author=Eddie Large and Stafford Hildred|isbn=1844541282|title=Larger Than Life: My Autobiography|publisher=John Blake}}</ref> When he was nine years old, the family moved again to [[Manchester]], where he attended Claremont Road Primary School<ref name=wythenshawe>[http://wythenshawe.btck.co.uk/FamousLocals/LittleandLarge Wythenshawe Famous locals Little and Large] Retrieved 11 February 2016</ref> and a [[grammar school]].<ref>''Who's Who on Television''. ITV Books, 1982</ref>  He played football as a schoolboy, becoming a supporter of nearby [[Manchester City]] which had its ground opposite his home<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/lifestyle/showbiz/heart-swap-for-eddie-large-1655690|title=Heart swap for Eddie Large|first=Evening|last=Chronicle|date=18 June 2003|website=nechronicle}}</ref> and maintained a life long devotion to the club. After he left school he worked as an electrician and was a singer.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Little and Large==\n{{main|Little and Large}}\nHe met singer and guitarist Cyril Meed in the Stonemason's Arms pub in [[Wythenshawe]] and they formed a double act following the reaction to Eddie's comic heckling of Cyril,<ref name=wythenshawe></ref> who switched to comedy. The duo then performed in northern clubs, turning professional in 1963.<ref>[https://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/showbiz/eddie-large-little-large-dies-18028667  Cathy Owen, \"Comedian Eddie Large of Little & Large has died\", ''Wales Online'', 2 April 2020</ref>  As Little and Large, the two men began their TV career on the talent show ''[[Opportunity Knocks (UK TV series)|Opportunity Knocks]]'' winning in 1971 and starred in many television comedy programmes, including their own series ''[[The Little and Large Show]]'' and the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] series ''[[Who Do You Do?]]'' doing impressions and also performing as [[pantomime]] stars. \n\nIn an interview in 2010, Large said that he and Syd Little had not spoken to each other for several years.<ref>{{cite news |author= |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/little-and-large-havent-spoken-for-a-long-time-1988413.html |title=Little and Large 'haven't spoken for a long time' |work=The Independent |date=1 June 2010 |accessdate=23 July 2013}}</ref> During the 2010\u201311 football season, football entertainment show ''[[Soccer AM]]'' produced comedy sketches with Peterborough footballer [[Mark Little (footballer)|Mark Little]], and Eddie Large, as the newly reformed Little and Large.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.socceram.com/story/0,21644,13871_6310041,00.html |title=Soccer AM &#124; Sky Sports |publisher=Soccer AM |date=13 August 2010 |accessdate=23 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\nLarge worked on the after-dinner circuit and, in the latter years of his life, performed some cameo acting roles in dramas such as ''[[The Brief (ITV)|The Brief]]'' and ''[[Blackpool (TV serial)|Blackpool]]''. In 2006 he appeared on a comedy edition of ''[[The Weakest Link (UK game show)|The Weakest Link]]'', but was eliminated prior to the penultimate round. His autobiography entitled ''Larger than Life'' was published in 2005. \n\nIn 2013, Large released his first single without Little, a parody of \"[[Je t'aime... moi non plus]]\" by [[Serge Gainsbourg]] entitled \"Gee Musky... Moi Non Plus\".{{cn|date=August 2018}}\n\n==Personal life==\nLarge lived in [[Portishead, Somerset|Portishead]], near [[Bristol]], with his wife Patsy and 26-year-old son.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-52136768|title=Comedian Eddie Large dies with Coronavirus|date=2020-04-02|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>  He also had two daughters and three grandchildren.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nAfter being admitted to hospital in March 2002 due to kidney problems, he underwent a [[heart transplant]] at [[Papworth Hospital]], Cambridge in 2003 at the age of 62, and recovered fully.{{cn|date=April 2020}} Large<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://daily-cyprus.com/2020/04/02/eddie-large-dies-aged-78-with-coronavirus/|title=Eddie Large Died at age of 78 with COVID19|date=2 April 2020|work=Daily Cyprus|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> was hospitalised for some weeks in late 2013 after tripping over a road sign near his Portishead home.<ref>{{cite web|title=Comedian Eddie Large in hospital after road sign fall|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-24971363|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref> \n\n==Death==\nLarge died on 2 April 2020 at [[Southmead Hospital]] in [[Bristol]] after contracting [[COVID-19]] while in hospital receiving treatment for heart failure.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peplow |first1=Gemma |title=Coronavirus: Little and Large comedian Eddie Large dies 'after contracting COVID-19 in hospital'|work=Sky News|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-little-and-large-comedian-eddie-large-dies-after-contracting-covid-19-in-hospital-11967427 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Large had suffered from kidney and heart problems for a number of years.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Eddie Large dies aged 78 |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/people/news/5726/rip-eddie-large/ |website=[[British Comedy Guide]] |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0488116}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Large, Eddie}}\n\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:British male comedians]]\n[[Category:Heart transplant recipients]]\n[[Category:People from Gorbals]]\n[[Category:People from Portishead, Somerset]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Manchester]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:British television personalities]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British comedian}}\n{{Recent death}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date= March  2020}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name              = Eddie Large\n| image             = Eddie Large.jpg\n| imagesize         = 180px\n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = Edward Hugh McGinnis\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1941|6|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|2020|4|2|1941|6|25|df=y}}\n| death_place       = [[Southmead Hospital]], [[Bristol]], England \n| medium            = Comedian\n| nationality       = Scottish\n| genre             = \n| subject           = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| spouse            = {{ubl|{{marriage|Sandra Bigwood|1965||end=div}}|{{marriage|Patsy Ann Scott|1983|<!--Year is omitted when marriage ends by death of subject of article-->}}}} \n| children          = 3\n| notable_work      = [[Little and Large]]\n}}\n\n'''Edward Hugh McGinnis''' (25 June 1941 \u2013 2 April 2020), better known by the stage name '''Eddie Large''', was a Scottish comedian. He was best known as one half of the double act [[Little and Large]], with [[Syd Little]].\n\n==Early life==  \nLarge was born Edward Hugh McGinnis in [[Glasgow]] in 1941. His father Teddy served as a [[Petty Officer]] in the [[Royal Navy]] during World War II and after he returned from the war the family moved to a [[tenement]] in [[Oatlands, Glasgow|Oatlands]].<ref name=Autobiography>{{cite book|date=1 July 2005|author=Eddie Large and Stafford Hildred|isbn=1844541282|title=Larger Than Life: My Autobiography|publisher=John Blake}}</ref> When he was nine years old, the family moved again to [[Manchester]], where he attended Claremont Road Primary School<ref name=wythenshawe>[http://wythenshawe.btck.co.uk/FamousLocals/LittleandLarge Wythenshawe Famous locals Little and Large] Retrieved 11 February 2016</ref> and a [[grammar school]].<ref>''Who's Who on Television''. ITV Books, 1982</ref>  He played football as a schoolboy, becoming a supporter of nearby [[Manchester City]] which had its ground opposite his home<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/lifestyle/showbiz/heart-swap-for-eddie-large-1655690|title=Heart swap for Eddie Large|first=Evening|last=Chronicle|date=18 June 2003|website=nechronicle}}</ref> and maintained a life long devotion to the club. After he left school he worked as an electrician and was a singer.{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Little and Large==\n{{main|Little and Large}}\nHe met singer and guitarist Cyril Meed in the Stonemason's Arms pub in [[Wythenshawe]] and they formed a double act following the reaction to Eddie's comic heckling of Cyril,<ref name=wythenshawe></ref> who switched to comedy. The duo then performed in northern clubs, turning professional in 1963.<ref>[https://www.walesonline.co.uk/lifestyle/showbiz/eddie-large-little-large-dies-18028667  Cathy Owen, \"Comedian Eddie Large of Little & Large has died\", ''Wales Online'', 2 April 2020</ref>  As Little and Large, the two men began their TV career on the talent show ''[[Opportunity Knocks (UK TV series)|Opportunity Knocks]]'' winning in 1971 and starred in many television comedy programmes, including their own series ''[[The Little and Large Show]]'' and the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] series ''[[Who Do You Do?]]'' doing impressions and also performing as [[pantomime]] stars. \n\nIn an interview in 2010, Large said that he and Syd Little had not spoken to each other for several years.<ref>{{cite news |author= |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/little-and-large-havent-spoken-for-a-long-time-1988413.html |title=Little and Large 'haven't spoken for a long time' |work=The Independent |date=1 June 2010 |accessdate=23 July 2013}}</ref> During the 2010\u201311 football season, football entertainment show ''[[Soccer AM]]'' produced comedy sketches with Peterborough footballer [[Mark Little (footballer)|Mark Little]], and Eddie Large, as the newly reformed Little and Large.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.socceram.com/story/0,21644,13871_6310041,00.html |title=Soccer AM &#124; Sky Sports |publisher=Soccer AM |date=13 August 2010 |accessdate=23 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\nLarge worked on the after-dinner circuit and, in the latter years of his life, performed some cameo acting roles in dramas such as ''[[The Brief (ITV)|The Brief]]'' and ''[[Blackpool (TV serial)|Blackpool]]''. In 2006 he appeared on a comedy edition of ''[[The Weakest Link (UK game show)|The Weakest Link]]'', but was eliminated prior to the penultimate round. His autobiography entitled ''Larger than Life'' was published in 2005. \n\nIn 2013, Large released his first single without Little, a parody of \"[[Je t'aime... moi non plus]]\" by [[Serge Gainsbourg]] entitled \"Gee Musky... Moi Non Plus\".{{cn|date=August 2018}}\n\n==Personal life==\nLarge lived in [[Portishead, Somerset|Portishead]], near [[Bristol]], with his wife Patsy and 26-year-old son.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-52136768|title=Comedian Eddie Large dies with Coronavirus|date=2020-04-02|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-GB}}</ref>  He also had two daughters and three grandchildren.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nAfter being admitted to hospital in March 2002 due to kidney problems, he underwent a [[heart transplant]] at [[Papworth Hospital]], Cambridge in 2003 at the age of 62, and recovered fully.{{cn|date=April 2020}} Large<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://daily-cyprus.com/2020/04/02/eddie-large-dies-aged-78-with-coronavirus/|title=Eddie Large Died at age of 78 with COVID19|date=2 April 2020|work=Daily Cyprus|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> was hospitalised for some weeks in late 2013 after tripping over a road sign near his Portishead home.<ref>{{cite web|title=Comedian Eddie Large in hospital after road sign fall|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-24971363|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref> \n\n==Personal life==\nLarge died on 2 April 2020 at [[Southmead Hospital]] in [[Bristol]] after contracting [[COVID-19]] while in hospital receiving treatment for heart failure.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peplow |first1=Gemma |title=Coronavirus: Little and Large comedian Eddie Large dies 'after contracting COVID-19 in hospital'|work=Sky News|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-little-and-large-comedian-eddie-large-dies-after-contracting-covid-19-in-hospital-11967427 |accessdate=2 April 2020 |date=2 April 2020}}</ref> Large had suffered from kidney and heart problems for a number of years.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Eddie Large dies aged 78 |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/people/news/5726/rip-eddie-large/ |website=[[British Comedy Guide]] |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0488116}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Large, Eddie}}\n\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:British male comedians]]\n[[Category:Heart transplant recipients]]\n[[Category:People from Gorbals]]\n[[Category:People from Portishead, Somerset]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Manchester]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:British television personalities]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "DESIGN COORDINATION", "label": "safe", "comment": "Formatting only.  Added sub section \"Death\" to remove death entry from \"Personal Life\" section.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eddie_Large"}
